Introduction to Computer Vision: Plant Seedlings Classification¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term. The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can actually benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor, could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human inolvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to Build a Convolutional Neural Netowrk to classify plant seedlings into their respective categories.

Data Dictionary¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The dataset can be download from Olympus.

  • The data file names are:

    • images.npy
    • Label.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to the images.npy file and the labels are also put into Labels.csv, so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

List of Species

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

def plot_images(images, labels):
    # Define the number of unique classes
    num_classes = 10

    # Get the unique categories (class labels)
    categories = np.unique(labels)

    # Create a dictionary to map labels to their corresponding names
    keys = dict(labels['Label'])

    # Define the number of rows and columns for the subplot grid
    rows = 3
    cols = 4

    # Create a figure for plotting
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

    # Loop through the grid of subplots
    for i in range(cols):
        for j in range(rows):
            # Generate a random index to select an image and label
            random_index = np.random.randint(0, len(labels))

            # Create a subplot at the current position in the grid
            ax = fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1)

            # Display the image from the 'images' array
            ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])

            # Set the title of the subplot to the corresponding label name
            ax.set_title(keys[random_index])

    # Show the plotted subplots
    plt.show()

# Intializing a sequential model
model1 = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension of images
model1.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

model1.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model1.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 16 neurons
model1.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model1.add(Dropout(0.3))
# Adding the output layer with 12 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model1.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))
# Adding Adam optimizer
opt=Adam()
# Compile model1
model1.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Generating the summary of the model1
model1.summary()

Observations¶

Here are some insights based on the classification report for Model 1:

Overall Performance: Model 1 achieves an accuracy of 0.59, indicating that it correctly classifies 59% of the samples in the test dataset. While this is better than random guessing, there is room for improvement.

Class Imbalance: There are notable variations in precision, recall, and F1-score across different classes. Some classes, like Class 1 and Class 10, have high precision and recall, suggesting good classification performance. However, others, like Class 0 and Class 4, have lower precision and recall, indicating challenges in distinguishing these classes.

Low Recall: Classes 0, 4, and 9 have particularly low recall values (0.15, 0.09, and 0.35, respectively). This means that the model struggles to correctly identify instances of these classes, and there may be a need to explore ways to improve recall for these classes.

Class 6: Class 6 stands out with relatively high precision (0.55) and high recall (0.77), resulting in a decent F1-score of 0.64. The model performs relatively well in correctly classifying this category.

Weighted Average F1-Score: The weighted average F1-score is 0.58, indicating the overall harmonic mean of precision and recall across all classes. It reflects the model's balanced performance across classes but suggests room for improvement.

Macro Average Metrics: The macro average (average across classes) precision, recall, and F1-score are around 0.53, indicating that, on average, the model's performance is moderate across all classes.

Opportunity for Improvement: Model 1 has shown potential for improvement, particularly in classes with low recall. Strategies such as data augmentation, fine-tuning hyperparameters, or using more complex models may help enhance overall performance.

Class 10: Class 10 has a relatively high F1-score of 0.78, suggesting that the model is particularly effective at classifying this category. Understanding the features that contribute to this performance may provide insights for improving other classes.

Observations¶

Here are some insights based on the classification report for Model 2:

Overall Performance: Model 2 demonstrates improved overall performance compared to Model 1, with an accuracy of 0.64. This indicates that it correctly classifies 64% of the samples in the test dataset.

Class Imbalance Handling: Model 2 appears to have addressed some class imbalance issues seen in Model 1. Several classes now have higher recall values, indicating improved performance in correctly identifying instances of those classes.

Class 4 (Zero Recall): Class 4 still exhibits a challenge with zero recall, indicating that the model is unable to correctly identify any instances of this class. This is a significant limitation that needs to be addressed.

High Precision: Classes 3 and 10 stand out with relatively high precision values (0.86 and 0.89, respectively). This suggests that the model is effective in correctly classifying instances for these categories.

Balanced F1-Scores: The F1-scores for most classes show a good balance between precision and recall, with weighted average and macro average F1-scores of 0.64 and 0.59, respectively.

Class 6: Class 6 continues to have moderate performance with a precision of 0.60 and a recall of 0.60, resulting in an F1-score of 0.60.

Class 10 (High Performance): Class 10 maintains its high F1-score of 0.85, indicating that the model excels in classifying this category. Understanding the features contributing to this performance can provide insights for improving other classes.

Class 7: Class 7 has improved with a higher recall (0.68) compared to Model 1, suggesting better performance in identifying instances of this class.

Class 1: Class 1 has relatively high precision (0.78) and recall (0.79), indicating good performance in correctly classifying this category.

Class 8: Class 8 also shows improvement with a precision of 0.71 and a recall of 0.67.

Class 11: Class 11 has a balanced precision-recall trade-off with a precision of 0.52 and a recall of 0.63.

Model 3¶

Model Performance Improvement¶

Reducing the Learning Rate:

Hint: Use ReduceLRonPlateau() function that will be used to decrease the learning rate by some factor, if the loss is not decreasing for some time. This may start decreasing the loss at a smaller learning rate. There is a possibility that the loss may still not decrease. This may lead to executing the learning rate reduction again in an attempt to achieve a lower loss.

In [ ]:
# Configure a learning rate reduction callback
learning_rate_reduction = ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_accuracy',   # Metric to monitor for reduction
    patience=3,               # Number of epochs with no improvement before reducing LR
    verbose=1,                # Verbosity level (1: moderate, 0: minimal)
    factor=0.5,               # Reduction factor (new LR = old LR * factor)
    min_lr=0.00001            # Minimum learning rate
)

# Intializing a sequential model
model3 = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 128 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension of images
model3.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model3.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

model3.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# Create a Sequential model (model4)
model4 = Sequential()

# Adding the convolutional part of the VGG16 model (vgg_model) from above
model4.add(vgg_model)

# Flattening the output of the VGG16 model because it is from a convolutional layer
model4.add(Flatten())

# Adding a dense hidden layer with 100 units and ReLU activation
model4.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))

# Adding dropout to prevent overfitting (30% dropout rate)
model4.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Adding the output layer with 12 neurons and softmax activation for multi-class classification
model4.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Using the Adam optimizer for training
opt = Adam()
